Step 1: Create Maven Project
		1. Create Simple project
		2. Group ID, Artifact ID is project name

Step 2: POM.xml
		1. Add dependency under dependencies --> 
		<dependencies>
			<dependency>
				1. Selenium Java -----> https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.seleniumhq.selenium/selenium-java
				2. apache poi --------> https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.apache.poi/poi
				3. apache poi-ooxml --> https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.apache.poi/poi-ooxml
				4. testng ------------> https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.testng/testng
				5. extent report -----> https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/com.aventstack/extentreports
				6. commons-io --------> https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/commons-io/commons-io
				7. commons-lang3 -----> https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.apache.commons/commons-lang3
				8. log4j-core --------> https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.apache.logging.log4j/log4j-core
				9. log4j-api ---------> https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.apache.logging.log4j/log4j-api
			</dependency>
		</dependencies>

3. As a regular practice for testers use --> src/test/java and src/test/resource

src/test/java ---> page object class, test class, utilities, base class
src/test/resource -> upload data, properties file, input data file

4. Create/ design project
		src/test/java :
						1. Page object folder
						2. test base folder
						3. test case folder
						4. utility folder
						
		Under main project create folder for:
					1. logs
					2. reports
					3. screenshots
					4. test data

5. classed under each folders in src/test/java
		1. Page object folder
				1. page object class - page object class will always contain constructor, locator, action methods
									   page object class should not contain any validation. if validation requires capture value and return to test class to validate
				2. In page object folder only we have to create 
									-  create one common class to initialize driver. 
											- create constructor and initialize driver
											- To initialize driver use PageFactory.initclass(driver,this)
									- create class for individual app page and extends common class to get browser
									- create constructor to get driver use super(driver) to get driver from common webdriver.
									- app page wise xpaths and methods to call and use in methods with @FindBy(xpath="")WebElement variable_Name
		2. Test Case folder
				1. create test case for each app page
				2. using testNG @BeforeTest , @Test, @AfterTest
				3. initialize browser and pass in page object class
				3. create common methods and move @BeforeTest and @AfterTest to use common across all test case class
				
6. Log4j
Log4j used for recording all the events in the form of text
logging level - All < Trace < Debug < Info < Warn < Error < Fatal < Off
the level covers the downstreams. Eg : Debug covers all the downstream like - Info,Warn,error,fatal,off

		1. Check in POM the following dependencies are added
				1. /org.apache.logging.log4j/log4j-core - (Mandatory)
				2. /org.apache.logging.log4j/log4j-api - (Mandatory)
				3. /org.apache.logging.log4j/log4j-slf4j-impl - (optional but it will manage slf4j error)
		
		2. Go to mvnrepository and check the latest version of centralized dependencies are added else update it in POM
		3. log4j requires log4j2.xml get it from official site and its a template once get it from apache site we have to based on our project requirements
		4. official site for template - https://logging.apache.org/log4j/2.3.x/manual/configuration.html (under additivity)
		** I took from the learning module
		
In log4j2.xml file
	There are 2 important things in log4j2.xml file
		1. Appenders - where to generate logs (Console/File)
		2. Loggers - what type of logs to generate (All < Trace < Debug < Info < Warn < Error < Fatal < Info)

log4j2.xml file explain : 
<Configuration status="INFO">
    <Properties>
        <Property name="log-path">./logs</Property>  ---------> Properties to choose where to save logs file
        <Property name="log-pattern">%d{yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss} %-5p %c{1}:%L - %m%n</Property>
    </Properties>
    
<Appenders>
        <Console name="Console" target="SYSTEM_OUT">  ---> Appender properties for Console
            <PatternLayout pattern="${log-pattern}"/>
        </Console>

        <RollingFile name="File" fileName="${log-path}/automation.log" ----> Appenders properties for File
                     filePattern="${log-path}/automation-%d{MM-dd-yyyy}-%i.log.gz">
            <PatternLayout pattern="${log-pattern}"/>
            <Policies>
                <TimeBasedTriggeringPolicy/>
                <SizeBasedTriggeringPolicy size="1MB"/>
            </Policies>
            <DefaultRolloverStrategy max="10"/>
        </RollingFile>
    </Appenders>

    <Loggers>
        <Root level="INFO">  ----> Loggers level properties
            <!--<AppenderRef ref="Console"/>-->
            <AppenderRef ref="File"/> ----> Loggers properties to choose in which form by appenders (console/file)
        </Root>
    </Loggers>	
</Configuration>

Log4j2 .xml and pom file is configured, then go to base/common method - beforeTest
			1. In common methods, initialize logger like how we do for driver
				outside the BeforeTest--> public Logger logger; - import org.apache.logging.log4j.Logger;
				
				In BeforeTest --> logger=LogManager.getLogger(this.getClass()); - import org.apache.logging.log4j.LogManager;
						LogManager is pre-define method in logger
						this will always point the current class which running
						.getClass() is used to capture class whichever running dynamically
			
			2. Once initialized in common method, that common will extend to any @Test methods on different class
				now just use ---> 	logger.info("<Give info message to be in console/File>")
									logger.All/Trace/Debug/Info/Warn/Error/Fatal/Off

 
